Phase 0 — Python Power-Up
Status: ✅ Complete
Overview
This phase rebuilt my Python skills from the ground up — not just syntax, but real fluency: writing clean, idiomatic code without hesitation.
What's Covered
Lesson 1 — Fundamentals
Variables, strings & f-strings, lists, dicts, tuples, sets, loops (enumerate, .items()), functions, conditionals.
Lesson 2 — List Comprehensions
Filtering and transforming data in a single line instead of multi-line loops — the most "Pythonic" tool used constantly in ML code.
Lesson 3 — Functions in Depth
*args (unnamed arguments → tuple), **kwargs (named arguments → dict), lambda functions, and passing functions as arguments. Practiced combining all three in business-style reporting functions.
Lesson 4 — Object-Oriented Programming
Classes, __init__, self, methods, inheritance, and super(). Built a parent/child class hierarchy (AIModel → FinanceModel / HealthModel) — the same pattern PyTorch uses for every neural network (class MyModel(nn.Module)).
Lesson 5 — File I/O & Error Handling
Reading/writing JSON and CSV files, try/except/finally, and handling common errors (FileNotFoundError, KeyError).
Lesson 6 — Modules & Environments
Built-in modules (os, random, math), installing packages with pip, virtual environments, and writing/importing a custom module (ai_utils.py).
Key Project
A multi-class hierarchy simulating an AI consulting business:

class AIModel:

    def __init__(self, name, accuracy, speed): ...

    def describe(self): ...

    def is_production_ready(self): ...

class FinanceModel(AIModel):

    def risk_check(self): ...

class HealthModel(AIModel):

    def safety_check(self): ...

Plus a function combining everything from this phase at once:

def summarize_models(*args, **kwargs):

    threshold = kwargs["threshold"]

    [print(f"{m['name']}: {m['accuracy']:.0%}")

     for m in args if m["accuracy"] > threshold]
